oversimplifying you can think of databases as being, uh, in one of two categories. Uh, there's

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:37.740
relational databases and then there's the newer NoSQL or object oriented databases. We'll focus

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:43.240
on the first one, uh, and that's mostly for historical reasons. They've been, uh, around for

00:02:43.979 --> 00:02:49.479
longer. Uh, the infrastructure around them in general, not just in R, is stronger. Uh, and very

00:02:49.479 --> 00:02:54.479
quickly relational databases and their management systems store data in columns and rows. These

00:02:56.880 --> 00:03:01.899
make up tables. It looks spreadsheet-y. Uh, they use SQL which is a language for querying data.

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:12.500
Uh, a few popular, uh, databases, uh, that are relational are, in this case open source, are

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:18.199
MySQL, Postgres, and SQLite. Recently for distributed systems you also have things like Apache

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:23.199
Hive and Cloudera Impala which are relational-like. Um, and most of these packages work really

00:03:25.539 --> 00:03:30.539
well, uh, with relational databases. There's nothing stopping them from working with, um, the,

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:38.660
um, NoSQL databases. There- there needs to be more infrastructure there though and that we

00:03:38.679 --> 00:03:43.720
haven't gotten to it yet. Uh, so I'm gonna skip over this a little bit and get right into the

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:49.320
packages. So the first foundational package, uh, that we're interested in when it comes to

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:56.100
databases in R is called DBI and it stands for database interface, uh, and the whole idea of DBI

00:03:56.100 --> 00:04:01.600
is that it's a standard, it's an interface, uh, that defines how you should interact with the

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:06.600
database from R. So basically it has, um, S3 generics which are, uh, functions that are

00:04:09.119 --> 00:04:14.119
implemented for particular types of connections. So DBI itself doesn't, uh, care what type of

00:04:16.859 --> 00:04:22.660
connection you have, it just says that whatever is your connection you have to implement this

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:27.899
method for connecting, that method for disconnecting, and a bunch of other methods. So the

00:04:27.899 --> 00:04:34.899
advantage of this is that you get, um, different databases using basically the same language and

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:38.980
that gives you a lot of portability in your code. You can basically migrate your database to

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:44.000
another system and be able to use, uh, a lot of your old code. Uh, so one thing that I wanna, uh,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
note particularly is that, uh, as I said, DBI itself doesn't care what is the particular

00:04:54.600 --> 00:05:01.540
database you're using. Uh, all of that work is done by other packages and these, uh, packages

00:05:01.579 --> 00:05:06.059
will implement all of these methods for a particular database, uh, or a database

00:05:06.059 --> 00:05:11.059
management system. So these are the so called DBI compliant backends, um, our SQLite, our

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:19.160
MySQL, our Postgres are all examples of DBI compliant packages, um, so you need to use both

00:05:21.559 --> 00:05:26.579
of them if you want to connect to, uh, a SQLite database. Um, so and if this sounds like

00:05:26.820 --> 00:05:31.820
extra work to you, again, the advantage is that by having DBI, um, you have a very portable, um,

00:05:40.899 --> 00:05:45.899
language, uh, for a lot of different packages. In practice, uh, DBI looks like this. You can

00:05:48.839 --> 00:05:53.839
create a connection by calling DB connect. In this case I am creating a, um, connection

00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:01.720
to, uh, SQLite database in memory. Uh, you can write a table, you can get a query, this is SQL

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:08.920
right here, so it, you have to be a little bit fluent in SQL and when you're done you need to

00:06:10.299 --> 00:06:14.839
disconnect your connection which is very important because if you forget to do this and you're

00:06:14.839 --> 00:06:19.540
doing a lot of queries and creating a lot of connections you will actually leak a lot of

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:24.540
connections. So the gist of it's pretty simple. Uh, one thing that I want to note in DBI

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:33.820
before we move on is that it also provides really good, um, SQL injection prevention, uh,

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:38.820
functions. So, uh, SQL injection is when, um, users, third parties can, uh, go to your app or

00:06:43.299 --> 00:06:48.299
go to your program and inject code that has basically malicious intent. So in this case even

00:06:49.299 --> 00:06:54.299
though the string here is asking for a name a user can do this, uh, and, and if you're not

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:05.480
escaping this correctly this can cause your database to lose a whole table. So this has

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:11.779
been a problem ever since relational databases have existed, uh, and the whole point of here,

00:07:11.779 --> 00:07:18.059
the punchline of this comic is that you need to sanitize your database input and DBI has a

00:07:18.079 --> 00:07:24.160
lot of functions for that. So keep that in mind. That is important. So moving on to ODBC. I'm

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:29.160
going to spend very little time on this. Uh, ODBC, uh, is yet another, uh, standard, yet

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:36.440
another specification. Uh, so ODBC, uh, unlike DBI however is independent of operating

00:07:40.239 --> 00:07:45.239
system, of programming language, and it really is just a standard API of how to interact

00:07:45.459 --> 00:07:50.459
with databases. How this relates to R is that very recently, uh, we have the ODBC package,

00:07:54.739 --> 00:07:59.739
ODBC now in lowercase, which is a DBI compliant backend. So what this means is that if you

00:08:03.079 --> 00:08:08.079
have an ODBC driver for a package that has been written by whomever, uh, that is not in R

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:13.700
because ODBC is not language dependent, and then you have DBI and ODBC, you don't need to

00:08:15.799 --> 00:08:20.799
write your own driver for whatever database you want to connect to if you already have the

00:08:21.239 --> 00:08:26.239
ODBC driver. So that's the real power of this, uh, and it really augments the power of DBI by

00:08:27.279 --> 00:08:32.280
extending it to so many other databases that didn't have specific drivers. Uh, in practice it

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:37.960
looks very similar to what we've seen already. You have DB connect, you have a series of, uh,

00:08:38.119 --> 00:08:43.119
arguments. One thing to note is that since, um, you're always connecting with ODBC, these

00:08:43.719 --> 00:08:48.739
arguments are actually the same always now. It's always, um, UID for example instead of user or

00:08:51.539 --> 00:08:56.539
username or one of the thousand variants that you can have. Uh, and then you can, uh,

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:02.840
continue doing, uh, doing a very similar job disconnecting at the end. Dplyr. Um, so the

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:08.520
idea, now that you know about DBI and you can use DBI for so many things, the idea, uh, to

00:09:12.119 --> 00:09:17.119
take it one level up is to not have to worry about SQL, um, and just use Dplyr syntax, use R

00:09:21.059 --> 00:09:26.059
code to talk to a database, to extract data, to insert data, uh, to transform data. Uh, so

00:09:26.859 --> 00:09:31.859
Dplyr extends and wraps a lot of DBI methods and you can do most of what you can do, what you

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:41.580
can do with DBI and SQL directly with Dplyr and R. Uh, there are a few things that you still

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:46.580
need DBI for because, um, Dplyr is not magic, uh, although it seems like it sometimes. Um, and

00:09:50.520 --> 00:09:55.719
there has been actually a very recent revamp of Dplyr, uh, and the introduction of a new

00:09:56.520 --> 00:10:01.520
package called Dbplyr, uh, so this is, uh, fresh off the presses. Um, the bottom line I think is

00:10:05.419 --> 00:10:12.140
if you ha- if you're used to R and if you're used to the Dplyr verbs, like filter and mutate

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:16.940
and group by and summarize, it's a very good, uh, idea to go with Dplyr. It also does a bunch

00:10:16.940 --> 00:10:22.979
of optimizations for you with SQL translation and lazy evaluation so you're never loading

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:29.280
data into R until you need it. Uh, so if Dplyr is good enough for you, it tends to be, uh, a

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:35.719
great idea to use it and I hope this slide makes it really clear why that's so. Um, as you can

00:10:35.719 --> 00:10:41.159
see we have exactly the same standard for connection that we have with DBI, but now to

00:10:41.159 --> 00:10:48.000
query it we are just using Dplyr, we're piping things, uh, it's very easy for us to read as

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.440
human beings, you have a connection, you ask for the table called city and then you ask for

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:59.039
the first two rows and that's it. It's very intuitive, there's no select asterisk from

00:10:59.039 --> 00:11:04.039
city limit to, uh, that we had to deal with before. So, finally, pool. Uh, so after all these

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:12.080
packages why do we need another one? Um, the problem that pool, uh, tries to solve is how- what

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:18.859
is the best way to interact with the database from Shiny? So Shiny brings its own set of

00:11:18.859 --> 00:11:24.320
constraints, uh, there- for every one session there's only a single R process and potentially

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:29.599
many users. Establishing connections to a remote database can take quite a while and they can

00:11:29.599 --> 00:11:36.599
go down at any time because of network problems or, uh, a bunch of other things. Um, so you're

00:11:36.599 --> 00:11:40.840
really in this conundrum that you don't want a fresh connection for every query that you make

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:45.679
for every user action because that would be so slow, but you also don't want one connection

00:11:45.700 --> 00:11:51.539
per app because what if it breaks down? What if there's two users trying to make a query at the

00:11:51.539 --> 00:11:56.539
same time? So the pool package, uh, is meant to solve this problem, uh, by creating a pool

00:11:59.080 --> 00:12:04.080
of connections and it- so it fetches the connections from the remote, uh, server and then it

00:12:06.859 --> 00:12:12.520
keeps them locally and you can check them out as you need and return them and it does this

00:12:12.539 --> 00:12:17.500
kind of behind a curtain so you don't even notice. It's actually very similar to how DBI looks

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:23.679
except for the creating and the closing of the pool itself. So the idea is that it's kind of

00:12:23.679 --> 00:12:28.520
like having one connection per query except that the connections now are local, uh, and are

00:12:28.520 --> 00:12:32.320
recycled. So every time you're done with a connection it goes back to the pool and it can be

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:38.119
used again. Uh, so it gives you, uh, usually very good performance and it takes care of

00:12:38.119 --> 00:12:43.140
connection management. So it is mainly- pool is mainly important for shiny apps, uh, because

00:12:45.539 --> 00:12:49.940
of this whole interactive context I was talking about, but it can be used in any other context

00:12:49.940 --> 00:12:55.479
without any problem. Uh, you might not need it necessarily, but it definitely doesn't hurt and

00:12:55.479 --> 00:13:01.880
it also integrates seamlessly with both DBI and dplyr. We'll be, uh, on CRAN really soon, uh,

00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:07.020
and to have an idea of what it looks like, as you can see we still have our connection, our

00:13:07.059 --> 00:13:12.059
disconnection, our query. The query is exactly the same as it is with dplyr or DBI, uh, and the

00:13:14.659 --> 00:13:19.559
only things really that change is that instead of, uh, calling dbconnect I'm calling dbpool and

00:13:19.559 --> 00:13:24.380
instead of calling dbdisconnect I'm calling poolclose and this takes care of making all the

